com.teamdev.jxbrowser.chromium

Class JSArray

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.teamdev.jxbrowser.chromium.JSValue
      • com.teamdev.jxbrowser.chromium.JSObject
        • com.teamdev.jxbrowser.chromium.JSArray

  • public class JSArray
extends JSObject
    Represents JavaScript Array object. The object represents a "proxy" object to existing JavaScript array. It can reference JavaScript array that was already disposed because the web page where the JavaScript array was initialized has been already unloaded/reloaded. In this case any attempt to use JSArray that references already disposed JavaScript array will cause the IllegalStateException error. To find out whether JavaScript array is still valid use the getContext().isDisposed() method.

      • get

        public JSValue get(int index)
        Returns JavaScript value at the given index in the JavaScript array. The index mustn't be negative. Returns "undefined" JavaScript value when the index is out of array bounds (e.g. more than the array size).
        Parameters:
        index - element position in the array. Must be > 0.
        Returns:
        JavaScript value at the given position in the JavaScript array.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalStateException - when array is already disposed or invalid.
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - when index is negative.

      • set

        public boolean set(int index,
                   java.lang.Object value)
        Updates/inserts JavaScript value at the given index in the JavaScript array. The index mustn't be negative. If the index is more than the array size, then array size will be extended, the give value will be inserted at the specified position, the values between the latest item in the array and the new index will be filled with JavaScript "undefined" values (e.g. the undefined "holes" will be created in the array).
        Parameters:
        index - element position in the array. Must be > 0. Can be more than array size.
        value - a new value associated with the property with the given index. Cannot be null or JSObject with a different JavaScript context.
        Returns:
        true when the given value was successfully inserted at the given index, otherwise returns false.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - when value is null or represents JSObject with a different JavaScript context.
        java.lang.IllegalStateException - when array is already disposed or invalid.
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - when index is negative.
        Since:
        6.7
